post_text:
Sharing some (mostly) good news...Interscholastic athletic guidance was released by Governor Cuomo today:

Low-risk fall sports can be played starting Sept. 21; high-risk sports can practice. All Department of Health guidelines must be followed. See the attached images for details.

The New York State Public High School Athletic Association will meet with Section Executive Directors & COVID Task Force Tuesday to review specific guidance. Most information specific to the Frontier League (our immediate region) and Section III (our NYS area) will be developed and released ASAP.

Regional virus levels and safe implementation will be monitored carefully.

Great news for most student-athletes and school reopening overall. Thank you to the entire community for helping NY remain safe for our students on and off the field!

post_text:
The Indian River Central School District will hold a series of three Public Sessions to discuss our plans for reopening and to answer questions and gather feedback from the community. These sessions will be held via Facebook Live (accessible at ircsd.org and facebook.com/IndianRiverCSD) at the following dates and times:

- Thursday, August 13th from 4-5PM
- Monday, August 17th from 6-7PM
- Thursday, August 20th from 11AM -12PM

In developing our reopening plan, it was of the utmost importance that community input and engagement guided our decision making. In an effort to address any concerns or answer questions you may have, you are encouraged to complete this form before our public sessions.

Our reopening plan is fluid and will change as necessary based on guidance from the state, CDC, and NYSED. Please visit our COVID-19 site regularly for updates: ircsd.org/covid-19

Submit your questions today: https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSfqHtlxwjkhk2J1whYSkcNvnvVbFD99-sgDA-bKeouT9lkHKw/viewform?usp=sf_link

post_text:
The health and safety of our students, our staff, and their families is our top priority, and we want students and employees to feel comfortable and safe returning to school. This plan has been created to balance the challenging physical restrictions of social distancing and healthy interaction with the real educational opportunities and needs of our students, recognizing that this will require great flexibility on the part of everyone involved. We will help keep our community safe while providing opportunities for learning—we will remain #WarriorStrong!

The site linked below will be frequently updated as we continue to work diligently to plan a safe and flexible start to the new school year.

IRCSD Reopening 2020-21: https://sites.google.com/ircsd.org/covid-19/reopening-2020-21

We All Live in a Watershed Poster Contest 2020 Winners

Indian River Middle School
July 8 at 10:37 AM ·

This year, IRMS had three winners from Mrs. Steblen's Grade 8 Living Environment class for the NYS DEC's "We All Live in A Watershed" Poster Contest. Their artwork will be displayed in 2021-2022 DEC posters that are distributed statewide. Usually we would recognize these students at the 8th grade awards night, but you know how that went this year! The three winners from IRMS are (in no particular order):

Ali VanTassel
Elias Pratt
Samantha Booth

Their artwork was selected from over 500 submissions in 33 schools across NYS.

Below is the link to the page that displays the 14 winners selected from around NYS, including the artwork from Ali, Elias, and Sam

https://www.dec.ny.gov/education/119627.html

Congratulations, Ali, Elias, and Samantha!

The Art Department would like to share with our Indian River friends and family a video tribute of awards, artwork, student smiles and well wishes as we make our way into a well-earned Summer vacation.

Congratulations and thank you to each and every artist that so bravely created work for the Salmon Run Mall Art Show this Spring and special recognition to all of our award winners! We are so proud of the work our students have accomplished this school year. Thank you all for your continued support and encouragement at home with our young artists during these trying times. Your encouragement fosters a spirit in these children that will continue to provide them considerable enjoyment within the arts. Thank you!

Please click the thumbnail below for a direct link to a Digital Gallery featuring each and every K-12 artwork from this year's Salmon Run Mall Art Show. Feel free to Download and Share your favorite artworks or the entire gallery!

https://gallery.robertfountain3.com/virtualmallartshow/

-Robert Fountain
District Art Coordinator

Indian River residents approved the 2020-2021 budget through Absentee Ballot on June 16, 2020.

The $89,844,680 budget received 759 favorable votes and 126 votes in opposition.

Winning candidates for the Board of Education seats received the following votes:
- Seat #1 William Backus - 650 Votes
- Seat #2 Robin Johnson - 749 Votes

Write-in candidates' vote totals are listed on the attached slide (with direct spelling).

Thank you to the community for your continued support!

REMINDER: IRCSD Budget Hearing TONIGHT (5/28/2020) at 6:30PM

Indian River District residents will be able to view and participate in tonight's 2020-2021 Budget Hearing via live stream on the IRCSD District Facebook page. post_text: Congratulations to Philly Primary student Alana Pounds, whose winning artwork will be displayed at the Jefferson County Sheriff's Office!
shared_text:
Jefferson County Sheriff's Office
April 30 at 5:43 PM ·

Earlier this month the Victims Assistance Center of Jefferson County announced an art contest for children of all ages inviting them to draw, color or paint an image representing law enforcement appreciation. The winners’ artwork would be displayed at local Sheriff Offices and Police departments. Today we were thrilled to see the results at the Public Safety Building, framed and ready to display!

Winner, ages 3-5: Leighton Anderson, age 3 (not pictured)
Winner, ages 6-9: Alana Pounds, age 8
Winner, ages 10-14: Nyah Chiodi, age 13
Winner, ages 15-18: Maddy Furhman, age 16

Leighton’s artwork will be displayed at the St. Lawrence County Sheriff’s Office. The other winners, and the artwork of ALL of the other great little artists that submitted entries, will be displayed at the Jefferson County Sheriff’s Office. We appreciate the hard work of all that participated!

post_text:
IRCSD community members: As announced today by the Governor, all schools in New York State will remain closed for the remainder of the 2019-20 school year. Please note that the distance learning opportunities and instructional guidelines that we have established will continue during this closure, as will our food service and basic school operations.

This decision is based on the need to protect our students, staff, and community. Information regarding summer programming at Indian River Central and throughout the state will be forthcoming later in May. Please stay tuned for more details regarding impacts of the extended closure on IRCSD planning and event programming.

Please stay safe, stay healthy, and remain #WarriorStrong!

post_text:
Warrior Family and friends...stay tuned for some updates from our school buildings regarding "next phase plans" for supporting our students' educational needs.

Even with minor adjustments to our educational plans, IRCSD will continue to take a slow, steady, flexible, and student-centered approach that prioritizes the most essential components of our curriculum. We are not expecting our students' workload to have any significant increase...yet the work will be focused on the most critical aspects of our curriculum. #lessismoreIRCSD

Stay safe, stay healthy, and remain #WarriorStrong!

The printing project began with area schools (including IRHS) and the list of those involved has grown to include manufacturing companies, architects and various community members.

LEGAL NOTICE

Notice is hereby given that meetings of the Indian River Board of Education scheduled for the month of May, to be held in the Indian River Board of Education Room- District Office Complex, have been changed to May 7, 2020 and May 21, 2020. There will not be meetings held on May 14, 2020 and May 28, 2020. Pursuant to the Governor’s Executive Order No. 202.1, these meetings are not open to the public in person, but will be available via live stream through our district Facebook page. These meetings will be recorded and subsequently transcribed.

By order of the Indian River Board of Education.
Philadelphia, New York

Cheryl McCormick
District Clerk

post_text:
Upload your Sidewalk Chalk Art & Inspiration photo here:
https://forms.gle/fAV75ajY86ynNoQ89

The Art Department welcomes our communities to participate in creating and sharing your sidewalk chalk art and inspirational messages with us during this difficult time.

Creating art and breathing in some fresh air is a wonderful idea and can relieve some stress. This project has been circulating the country for a few weeks now and with warmer sunnier days in our future, we're looking forward to our chance to participate too!

Students and families are encouraged to share a photo of their fun and finished work with us. We'll then create a video of all of the artwork to share with our IR community! We're looking forward to seeing your artwork! We miss you and look forward to creating with you all again soon!

post_text:
IRCSD families and community members...at the order of Governor Cuomo, all NY schools will remain closed until at least April 29th to help maintain social distancing guidelines. This is an extension of the two-week closure increments put in place earlier through Executive Order.

Additionally, June 2020 Regents exams are expected to be canceled. The official announcement and details will be made available to NY schools and the public after April 7th.

The Governor and the NY State Education Department will continue to review status and provide guidance on school closures, assessments, graduation, and all related programmatic items. IRCSD will share updates when available.

Thank you for your understanding as well as everything you are doing to keep yourselves and the entire community safe!

Mrs. Dobmeier, Superintendent of Schools

The NYS Office of Children and Family Services (OCFS) is trying its best to support families in addressing their need for high-quality childcare. The OCFS is asking parents or caregivers who require childcare to complete an OCFS Parent Need for Childcare survey.

Based upon the information you provide about your job, employer, number of children, and financial need, the OCFS may be able to help you to locate the childcare program you need.

In addition, the OCFS website has several childcare resources available for those in need.

We hope that you find these resources to be valuable in your search for quality childcare during this unprecedented time. Do not hesitate to take advantage of what the OCFS has to offer.

It is very important to remember that children look to adults for guidance on how to react to stressful events. If parents seem overly worried, children’s anxiety may rise. Parents should reassure children that health and school officials are working hard to ensure that people throughout the country stay healthy. However, children also need factual, age appropriate information about the potential
seriousness of disease risk and concrete instruction about how to avoid infections and spread of disease. Teaching children positive preventive measures, talking with them about their fears, and giving them a sense of some control over their risk of infection can help reduce anxiety.

Parent Resource: Talking to Children About COVID-19 (Coronavirus): https://drive.google.com/file/d/13nwSW0iyYNgloo3r4KEH_wcR1Jmg0W1Y/view?usp=sharing

IRCSD continues to work with public health officials and local education leaders to make determinations about the cancellation of events, field trips, and school status.

As of this afternoon, Friday, March 13th, school will remain in session unless otherwise directed. We will continue to monitor the situation at the state and local levels and follow guidance received. All preventative practices (cleaning/disinfecting, limitation of contact, good hygiene reinforcement, etc.) are in full force.

Recent guidance from the CDC recommends that schools assess group gatherings and events and consider postponing non-critical gatherings and events. At this time, we are postponing the Alumni Basketball game and the High School Musical to dates yet to be determined.

We will evaluate the following week's events and activities in consultation with Jefferson County Public Health and will notify the school community as soon as possible through normal channels - official social media, website, and direct message.

Thank you for your flexibility and understanding.

The Indian River CSD students and community are uniting to find out what 1 million really means. How much would one million pennies weigh? How much space would it take up? How much money is it? What is a penny made out of? Whose face is on the penny?

This project will enhance the learning opportunities we provide our K-12 students within all academic disciplines. The pennies will be collected in each of the buildings as well as in the community, thanks to the support of our local businesses. They will be added to the large, see-through, student built container that is located in the High School lobby. Once the pennies have been collected and displayed, all the money will be donated to the Jefferson County SPCA!.

Do you know what 1 million pennies will look like? Help us find out! Visit ircsd.org/pennies for more information.

post_text:
Congratulations to Chanse Carpenter at Philadelphia Primary School!

Chanse was selected as the “Superintendents’ Artist of the Month”. Chanse has demonstrated critical thinking, creativity, and the desire to complete exceptional artwork. The competition amongst her peers was rigorous.

It was first an honor for Chanse's artwork to be displayed in the District Office for personnel, the community, and the Board of Education to enjoy for the last month. From that display, her piece was the one and only selected by the Superintendents to receive this prestigious “Artist of the Month” award.

We are incredibly pleased with the artwork all our artists are creating; they continue to prove they are learning each day to view their world creatively, critically, and with open eyes.

We look forward to continuing to highlight and honor the hard work and accomplishments of our young artists throughout this school year.

Well done, Chanse!

Mrs. Dobmeier - Superintendent
Mr. Decker - Assistant Superintendent
Mr. Fountain - District Art Coordinator
Mrs. Carlow - K-3 Art Teacher

FYI - School will resume at Antwerp Primary on Tuesday, January 21st. Though there is still a water advisory in place, we will hold school at APS tomorrow to maintain a regular routine for students and staff. (There is sufficient water pressure for toilets and general non-potable usage.)

We have taken the appropriate steps to ensure we have enough bottled drinking water available and will maintain sanitary practices until the water advisory is lifted. Thank you to our students, parents and staff for your understanding, and thank you to our hard working community members for assistance.

If you have any questions, please contact Antwerp Primary School on Tuesday.

IMPORTANT MESSAGE FOR MIDDLE SCHOOL FAMILIES:

Good morning Middle School Families - In exercising and abundance of caution when alerted by our safety system to an odor associated with our heating system, we felt the need to evacuate our staff and students to the high school until the situation could be rectified by authorities and or buildings and grounds department. At this time our students have been safely evacuated to our high school theatre. The appropriate people are on site working to fix the situation and we are working to have students back in classrooms as soon as possible. If you have questions, please contact the district office at 315-642-0125.

The Celebration of Life that was originally scheduled for Philadelphia Fire Hall on Thursday has been changed to Indian River High School. We greatly appreciate the efforts of Tammi Dindl and the IR Pop Warner Association in facilitating this evening. The event is slated to run from 5:30-7:30pm. At 6:00 we will have a welcome followed by comments from Pastor Kirk Gilcrest of the New Life Christian Church. Our desire for this evening is to provide a chance to talk, share stories, show pictures, and most importantly care for each other.

Sincerely,
Brian A. Moore
Principal

Indian River High School
January 7 at 10:30 PM ·

Indian River Community,

As we navigate the days ahead and begin to process this unimaginable tragedy our focus is on supporting all those impacted. We will maintain the Student Care Center in the library as we open school on Wednesday. This Care Center includes numerous counselors, mental health professionals, teachers, and staff. Please contact the school at 315-642-3427 if you are in need of any assistance. We ask you to keep the families in your thoughts during this most challenging time. As a Warrior Family we must do our best to gain strength from one another.

Sincerely,

Brian A. Moore
Principal

post_text:
For Immediate Release:

Dear Parents/Guardians,

This is the most difficult message I’ve ever had to write as a principal. It is with tremendous sadness that I share with you the news of a tragic loss in our Warrior community. Last night, two Indian River High School students were killed in a car accident. We are not able to provide any further details at this time, but we do want you to know that counseling and support are available for any member of our school community.

The Indian River Crisis Team is on hand today along with school and district administration to help students and staff cope with this heartbreaking news. Counselors and other support staff will continue to be available for students, teachers and families. Please contact the school at 315-642-3427 if you are in need of assistance, have any questions or wish to express concerns.

Sincerely,

Brian A. Moore
Principal

post_text:
Congratulations to Vivian McFadden at the High School!

Vivian was selected as the “Superintendents’ Artist of the Month”. Vivian has demonstrated critical thinking, creativity, and the desire to complete exceptional artwork. The competition amongst her peers was rigorous.

It was first an honor for Vivian's artwork to be displayed in the District Office for personnel, the community, and the Board of Education to enjoy for the last month. From that display, her piece was the one and only selected by the Superintendents to receive this prestigious “Artist of the Month” award.

We are incredibly pleased with the artwork all our artists are creating; they continue to prove they are learning each day to view their world creatively, critically, and with open eyes.

We look forward to continuing to highlight and honor the hard work and accomplishments of our young artists throughout this school year.

Well done Vivian!

Mrs. Dobmeier- Superintendent
Mr. Decker- Assistant Superintendent
Mr. Fountain- District Art Coordinator
Mrs. Tuttle- 9-12th Grade Art Teacher

post_text:
Tuesday, December 10 at 8 pm, WPBS hosts its second-annual festive high school concert for the Holidays. Nine select high school choirs from Watertown, Indian River, South Jefferson, Lowville, South Lewis, Beaver River, Gouverneur, Carthage, and Pulaski perform holiday favorites and seasonal hymns.

Indian River High School, under the choral direction of Shavon Lloyd and dance choreographer Tricia Moore, perform “Pentatonix Medley,” an inspiring arrangement that includes “Hark, The Herald Angels Sing,” “God Rest Ye Merry Gentlemen,” “Coventry Carol,” and “O Come All Ye Faithful.”

High School Holiday Concert: 2019 will air on WPBS on Tuesday, December 10 at 8 pm; Sunday, December 22 at 2 pm, and Wednesday, December 25 at 3:30 pm. The concert can also be seen online at watch.wpbstv.org beginning Tuesday, December 10.

Indian River Middle School
December 4, 2019 at 1:47 PM ·

Congratulations to Camila Quintero-Riano at the Middle School!

Camila was selected as the “Superintendents’ Artist of the Month”. Camila has demonstrated critical thinking, creativity, and the desire to complete exceptional artwork. The competition amongst her peers was rigorous.

It was first an honor for Camila’s artwork to be displayed in the District Office for personnel, the community, and the Board of Education to enjoy for the last month. From that display, her piece was the one and only selected by the Superintendents to receive this prestigious “Artist of the Month” award.

We are incredibly pleased with the artwork all our young artists are creating; they continue to prove they are learning each day to view their world creatively, critically, and with open eyes.

We look forward to continuing to highlight and honor the hard work and accomplishments of our young artists throughout this school year.

Well done Camila!

Mrs. Dobmeier- Superintendent
Mr. Decker- Assistant Superintendent
Mr. Fountain- District Art Coordinator
Mrs. Young- 7-8th Grade Art Teacher
